data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already threw `InvalidOperationException` for sync operations by default, but you could opt back in via the sync-over-async compatibility flag. **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** All four of your sync calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

**Affected methods:**
| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

**Fix — convert to async:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `async Task<T>` return types replace synchronous returns; callers must be updated to `await`.
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; no I/O occurs until `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- This change is Cosmos-specific; the relational providers still support sync APIs.
